00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:52.280
"How can one obtain public
persistent thumbnail links for

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:57.600
files?" Right now, what you get
in the file metadata is a

00:05:57.600 --> 00:06:00.140
short-lived thumbnail link.

00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:04.150
So whenever you want the
thumbnail for a file, you

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:05.970
should get the file
metadata first.

00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:09.920
And then, check the
thumbnail link.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.740
Because that link might
have changed.

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:16.130
There is no way to get a
persistent thumbnail link for

00:06:16.130 --> 00:06:18.390
files from the API.

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:22.230
What we can say is of course,
you can store the

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:23.470
thumbnail on your side.

00:06:23.470 --> 00:06:26.640
So you know that the thumbnail
link will expire.

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:29.530
But you go fetch it
the first time.

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:30.680
Fetch the thumbnail.

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:32.190
Store it somewhere
on your side--

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:36.250
or even on Drive, somewhere
on your Drive account.

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:39.980
And then, [? serve ?]
that instead.

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:42.720
I should also remind you that
thumbnails can change.

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:47.505
Because any time, the user that
owns the file can change

00:06:47.505 --> 00:06:49.620
the thumbnail, replace
it with a new one.

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:53.710
So that's another reason why
we don't have a static

00:06:53.710 --> 00:06:55.530
persistent thumbnail link.

00:06:55.530 --> 00:06:57.760
So that we force you
to get a new one.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:00.170
And if the new one
is changed--

00:07:00.170 --> 00:07:01.260
I mean, it's a new one.

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:04.750
Then, you always get it
instead of reusing the

00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:05.860
previous one.

00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:10.290
But if you don't mind risking
that, you can always download

00:07:10.290 --> 00:07:12.150
