00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:54.090
Jay--

00:08:54.090 --> 00:08:55.710
"What's the status
of the Drive API

00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:57.950
migrations between accounts?

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:00.730
We need the ability to identify
users shared on a

00:09:00.730 --> 00:09:04.090
file in order to replicate
the ACLs."

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:04.510
So let's see.

00:09:04.510 --> 00:09:06.380
What's the point here?

00:09:06.380 --> 00:09:11.660
I think the context is of Google
Apps domain, where

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:15.010
domain administrators
want to move files

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:17.300
from a user to another.

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:23.250
And right now, with the API,
whenever you share something,

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.640
we only address those
users by IDs--

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:27.770
unique IDs--

00:09:27.770 --> 00:09:30.430
but not email addresses.

00:09:30.430 --> 00:09:35.100
So for most cases,
IDs are fine.

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:41.730
For instance, when you're in
these Google Apps domain

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:45.710
environment, where you can
know the user IDs for all

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:48.370
users in your domain.

00:09:48.370 --> 00:09:53.220
And the broader case may have
files shared to several users.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:54.080
They're not in the domain.

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:58.500
And for those, you're not
getting the email address.

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:04.400
We are still working on this in
the sense that we need to

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:06.130
find the perfect trade-off
between the

00:10:06.130 --> 00:10:09.800
functionality and privacy.

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:12.690
So right now, all you
get is the ID.

00:10:12.690 --> 00:10:15.380
And that is fine for
most use cases.

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:18.400
For instance, in the Google Apps
domain case, you can use

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:19.250
service accounts.

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:24.050
And I also have a page here in
our Docs that explains how to

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:25.900
perform Google Apps domain-wide

00:10:25.900 --> 00:10:27.360
delegation of authority.

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.870
So what is explained here?

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:33.610
You can use a service account
as a domain admin to

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:37.030
impersonate other users
in a domain and act

00:10:37.030 --> 00:10:38.260
on behalf of them.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:41.950
This is usually what domain
admins want or need.

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:46.210
For what concerns the broader
case, we're still working on

00:10:46.210 --> 00:10:46.930
the trade-off.

00:10:46.930 --> 00:10:51.160
So still, this is a common
feature request.

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:52.970
So this is not the first
time we hear about it.

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:58.400
And we have a lot of discussions
about it.

00:10:58.400 --> 00:10:59.920
Please bear with
us a bit more.

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:05.390
And we will update you on what
the decision will be.

00:11:05.390 --> 00:11:07.120
Just remember this is
a privacy concern.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:09.290
So we take it really,
really seriously.

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:17.020
